         <head>NOTES <hi rend="small">TO THE </hi>POEM <hi rend="small">OF </hi> THE
                        BROTHERS.</head>
         <div xml:id="note1b">
            <head>
               <hi rend="small">NOTE I. </hi>
            </head>
            <p rend="note">Page 26—line 20 “There were two springs that
                            bubbled side by side.” The impressive circumstance here described,
                            actually took place some years ago in this country, upon an eminence
                            called Kidstow Pike, one of the highest of the mountains that surround
                            Hawes-water. The summit of the pike was stricken by lightning; and every
                            trace of one of the fountains disappeared, while the other continued to
                            flow as before.</p>
         </div>
         <div xml:id="note2b">
            <head>
               <hi rend="small">NOTE II. </hi>
            </head>
            <p rend="note">Page 29—line 5 “The thought of death sits easy on
                            the man,” &amp;c. There is not any thing more worthy of remark in
                            the manners of the inhabitants of these mountains, than the
                            tranquillity, I might say indifference, with which they think and talk
                            upon the subject of death. Some of the country church-yards, as here
                            described, do not contain a single tombstone, and most of them have a
                            very small number.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
